            "content": {
                "raw": "Yes, it's an intentional design decision, but I'd argue that it's ultimately a mistake, at least for the specific case of parallelism.\n\nLet's say I'm a new yt user.  I see in the docs that yt works in parallel and I can load data with `yt.load`.  Unfortunately, whenever I actually try to run in parallel, nothing happens for some reason.\n\nI'd argue that if we want to have extreme empathy for our users, we shouldn't force them to import yt in a certain way to access a basic feature like parallelism.",
                "html": "<p>Yes, it's an intentional design decision, but I'd argue that it's ultimately a mistake, at least for the specific case of parallelism.</p>\n<p>Let's say I'm a new yt user.  I see in the docs that yt works in parallel and I can load data with <code>yt.load</code>.  Unfortunately, whenever I actually try to run in parallel, nothing happens for some reason.</p>\n<p>I'd argue that if we want to have extreme empathy for our users, we shouldn't force them to import yt in a certain way to access a basic feature like parallelism.</p>",
                "markup": "markdown"
            },
